The '''Digital Markets Act''' ('''DMA''')<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://data.europa.eu/eli/reg/2022/2065/oj/eng|title=Regulation - 2022/2065 - EN - EUR-Lex}}</ref> is an [[Regulation (European Union)|EU regulation]] that aims to make the [[digital economy]] fairer and more contestable. The regulation entered into force on 1 November 2022 and became applicable, for the most part, on 2 May 2023.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Regulation (EU) 2022/1925 of the European Parliament and of the Council of 14 September 2022 on contestable and fair markets in the digital sector and amending Directives (EU) 2019/1937 and (EU) 2020/1828 (Digital Markets Act) |url=https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2022/1925/oj |access-date=2022-10-13 |website=[[EUR-Lex]] |language=en |publication-date=2022-10-22 |archive-date=13 October 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221013001351/https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2022/1925/oj |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=":33">{{Cite web |last=Liberatore |first=Francesco |date=2022-10-13 |title=DMA: EU Publishes The New Digital Markets Act |url=https://www.consumerprivacyworld.com/2022/10/dma-eu-publishes-the-new-digital-markets-act/ |access-date=2022-10-13 |website=Consumer Privacy World |publisher=[[Squire Patton Boggs]] |language=en-US |archive-date=13 October 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221013225201/https://www.consumerprivacyworld.com/2022/10/dma-eu-publishes-the-new-digital-markets-act/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

The DMA aims to ensure a higher degree of competition in European digital markets by preventing large companies from abusing their market power and by allowing new players to enter the market.<ref name="auto">{{cite news|last=Amaro|first=Silvia|date=December 15, 2020|title=EU announces sweeping new rules that could force breakups and hefty fines for Big Tech|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/12/15/digital-markets-act-eus-new-rules-on-big-tech.html|publisher=[[CNBC]]|access-date=December 29, 2020|archive-date=23 October 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221023165234/https://www.cnbc.com/2020/12/15/digital-markets-act-eus-new-rules-on-big-tech.html|url-status=live}}</ref> This [[Regulation (European Union)|regulation]] targets the largest [[Digital platform (infrastructure)|digital platforms]] operating in the European Union. They are also known as "gatekeepers" due to the "durable" market position in some digital sectors and because they also meet certain criteria related to the number of users, their turnovers, or capitalisation.<ref name=":11" /><ref name=":02"/><ref name=":13"/> Twenty-two services across six companies (deemed "gatekeepers") – [[Alphabet (company)|Alphabet]], [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]], [[Apple (company)|Apple]], [[ByteDance]], [[Meta Platforms|Meta]], and [[Microsoft]] – were identified as "core platform services" by the EU in September 2023.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.engadget.com/eu-confirms-the-six-tech-giants-subject-to-its-strict-new-competition-laws-161917822.html | title=EU confirms the six tech giants subject to its strict new competition laws | date=6 September 2023 }}</ref> 
These companies had until 6 March 2024 to comply with all of the Act's provisions.<ref name=":39">{{Cite web |date=2022-10-31 |title=Digital Markets Act: rules for digital gatekeepers to ensure open markets enter into force |url=https://ec.europa.eu/commission/presscorner/detail/en/ip_22_6423 |access-date=2023-03-02 |website=European Commission |language=en |archive-date=27 February 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230227231533/https://ec.europa.eu/commission/presscorner/detail/en/IP_22_6423 |url-status=live }}</ref>

The list of obligations includes prohibitions on combining data collected from two different services belonging to the same company (e.g., in the case of Meta, its social network [[Facebook]] and its communication platform [[WhatsApp]]);<ref name=":30" /> provisions for the protection of platforms' business users (including advertisers and publishers); legal instruments against the self-preferencing methods used by platforms for promoting their own products (e.g., preferential results for Google's products or services when using [[Google Search]]);<ref name=":23" /> provisions concerning the pre-installation of some services (e.g., [[Android (operating system)|Android]]);<ref name=":31" /> provisions related to [[Product bundling|bundling]] practices; and provisions for ensuring [[interoperability]], [[Data portability|portability]], and access to data for businesses and end-users of platforms.<ref name=":02"/> There are also provisions to ensure the end user can remove any pre-installed software.<ref>{{Citation |title=(49) - Regulation (EU) 2022/1925 of the European Parliament and of the Council of 14 September 2022 on contestable and fair markets in the digital sector and amending Directives (EU) 2019/1937 and (EU) 2020/1828 (Digital Markets Act) (Text with EEA relevance) |date=2022-09-14 |url=https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/?uri=CELEX:32022R1925 |access-date=2024-09-11 |language=en}}</ref> Non-compliance may lead to sanctions, including fines of up to 10% of the worldwide turnover.<ref name=":02">{{Cite web|last=Caffarra|first=Cristina|date=5 January 2021|title=The European Commission Digital Markets Act: A translation|url=https://voxeu.org/article/european-commission-digital-markets-act-translation|url-status=live|website=Vox EU|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210105171018/https://voxeu.org/article/european-commission-digital-markets-act-translation |archive-date=5 January 2021 }}</ref><ref name=":13" />

According to the European Commission, the main objective of this regulation is to regulate the behaviour of the so-called "Big Tech" firms within the European Single Market and beyond.<ref name=":12">{{Cite web|title=The Digital Services Act package &#124; Shaping Europe's digital future|url=https://digital-strategy.ec.europa.eu/en/policies/digital-services-act-package|access-date=2022-04-12|website=digital-strategy.ec.europa.eu|language=en}}</ref> The Commission aims to guarantee a fair level of competition ("level playing field"<ref name=":12"/>) on the highly concentrated digital European markets, which are often characterised by a "winner takes all" configuration.<ref name=":13"/>

The DMA covers eight different sectors, which it refers to as Core Platforms Services (CPS). Due to the presence of gatekeepers who, to a certain degree, affect the market contestability, the CPS are considered problematic by the European Commission:
* online search engines (e.g. [[Google Search]]);
* online intermediation services (e.g. [[Google Play|Google Play Store]], [[App Store (Apple)|Apple's App Store]]);
* social networks (e.g. [[Facebook]]);
* video sharing platforms (e.g. [[YouTube]]);
* communication platforms (e.g. [[WhatsApp]], [[Gmail]]);
* advertising services (e.g. [[Google Ads]]);
* operating systems (e.g. [[Android (operating system)|Android]], [[iOS]]);
* cloud services (e.g. [[Amazon Web Services]]).<ref name=":11" />
In April 2024, [[Reuters]] reported on data from six companies which showed that in the first month after the regulations were implemented, independent browsers had seen a spike in users. The [[Cyprus]]-based Aloha Browser said users in the EU jumped 250% in March. [[Norway]]-based [[Vivaldi (web browser)|Vivaldi]], [[Germany]]-based [[Ecosia]] and [[United States]]-based [[Brave (web browser)|Brave]] have also seen user numbers rise following the new regulation.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Mukherjee |first=Supantha |date=2024-04-10 |title=www.reuters.com |website=[[Reuters]] |url=https://www.reuters.com/technology/eus-new-tech-laws-are-working-small-browsers-gain-market-share-2024-04-10/ }}</ref>

== Background ==
===EU Competition policy rules===
The present rules applied within the European Union with regard to digital markets are derived from European and national legislation. Under these circumstances, the basis for competition rules in the EU is established by Articles 101 and 102 of the Treaty on the Functioning of the European Union (TFEU). Article 101 addresses anti-competitive agreements and concerted practices that may affect trade between members states or reduce competition in the common market. Article 102 aims to tackle the abuse of dominant positions.<ref name=":22">{{Cite web|last=Parenti|first=R|date=December 2020|title=Competition policy|url=https://www.europarl.europa.eu/factsheets/en/sheet/82/competition-policy|url-status=live|website=European Parliament|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180712060055/http://www.europarl.europa.eu:80/factsheets/en/sheet/82/competition-policy |archive-date=12 July 2018 }}</ref> All players operating in the common market are therefore subject to these provisions. European and national authorities have identified the need to strengthen the current legislation, given the structural problems that are not covered.<ref>{{Cite web|last=EUROPEAN COMMISSION|date=June 2020|title=New Competition Tool ('NCT')|url=https://ec.europa.eu/competition/consultations/2020_new_comp_tool/new_comp_tool_inception_impact_assessment.pdf|url-status=live|website=European Commission|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210525123353/https://ec.europa.eu/competition/consultations/2020_new_comp_tool/new_comp_tool_inception_impact_assessment.pdf |archive-date=25 May 2021 }}</ref>

===Digital policy in the EU===
The Digital Markets Act is in line with the legislative developments undertaken by the [[Juncker Commission]] between 2014 and 2019. 
One of the most important pieces of EU digital legislation is represented by the EU copyright rules. This has led to the protection, payment, and recognition of workers in thirty-three sectors and it aims to reward creativity, stimulate investment in the creative sector.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|last=European Commission|date=October 2020|title=Shaping the Digital Single Market|url=https://ec.europa.eu/digital-single-market/en/shaping-digital-single-market|url-status=live|website=European Commission|archive-url=https://digitalmarket.sg/learn/shaping-digital-single-market/https://ec.europa.eu/digital-single-market/en/shaping-digital-single-market |archive-date=30 October 2020 }}</ref> Another relevant achievement can be considered the implementation of the [[General Data Protection Regulation]] (GDPR) in 2016.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Skiera |first=Bernd |title=The impact of the GDPR on the online advertising market |date=2022 |others=Klaus Miller, Yuxi Jin, Lennart Kraft, René Laub, Julia Schmitt |isbn=978-3-9824173-0-1 |location=Frankfurt am Main |oclc=1303894344}}</ref> This regulation sets out the new European framework for the use and circulation of personal data and has a significant impact on the major digital players.<ref>{{Cite web|last=European Commission|title=Data protection in the EU|url=https://ec.europa.eu/info/law/law-topic/data-protection/data-protection-eu_en|url-status=live|website=European Commission|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180428112513/https://ec.europa.eu/info/law/law-topic/data-protection/data-protection-eu_en |archive-date=28 April 2018 }}</ref> In addition, the regulation on platform-to-business trading practices (P2B) has been established to create a fair, transparent and predictable business environment for smaller businesses and traders on online platforms. This regulation has applied in July 2020 and prevents market distortion, encourages healthy competition and prohibits unfair practices.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Ryan|first=T|date=2020|title=The Platform to Business Regulation (the 'P2B Regulation') – why worry?|url=https://www.dacbeachcroft.com/en/gb/articles/2020/august/the-platform-to-business-regulation-the-p2b-regulation-why-worry/|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201001093438/https://www.dacbeachcroft.com/en/gb/articles/2020/august/the-platform-to-business-regulation-the-p2b-regulation-why-worry/ |archive-date=1 October 2020 }}</ref>

== Legislative procedure ==
The Digital Markets Act proposal was submitted by the [[European Commission]] to the [[European Parliament]] and to the [[Council of the European Union]] on 15 December 2020. Along with the [[Digital Services Act]] (DSA),<ref name="auto1">{{cite news |last1=Espinoza |first1=Javier |last2=Hindley |first2=Scott |date=December 16, 2019 |title=Brussels'plans to tackle digital 'gatekeepers' spark fevered debate |url=https://app.ft.com/content/22bda533-db74-4a3d-917b-75ac23c0f27f |work=[[Financial Times]] |access-date=December 29, 2020 |archive-date=30 October 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211030131914/https://app.ft.com/content/22bda533-db74-4a3d-917b-75ac23c0f27f |url-status=live }}</ref> the DMA is part of the commission's European Digital Strategy entitled ''Shaping Europe's Digital Future''.<ref name=":12" /> The proposals were presented by the [[Executive Vice President of the European Commission for A Europe Fit for the Digital Age]], [[Margrethe Vestager]], and by the [[European Commissioner for Internal Market]], [[Thierry Breton]], as members of the [[Von der Leyen Commission I|Von der Leyen Commission]].<ref name=":12" />

On 23 November 2021, the Parliament's [[European Parliament Committee on the Internal Market and Consumer Protection|Committee on the Internal Market and Consumer Protection]] (IMCO) adopted its position on the DMA proposal, and the text was adopted in plenary session of the European Parliament on 15 December 2021.<ref name=":34">{{cite magazine |last1=Radosavljevic |first1=Zoran |date=December 15, 2021 |title=EU parliament adopts regulation targeting internet giants |url=https://www.euractiv.com/section/digital-single-market/news/eu-parliament-adopts-regulation-targeting-internet-giants/ |magazine=[[EurActiv]] |access-date=May 29, 2022 |archive-date=29 May 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220529092539/https://www.euractiv.com/section/digital-single-market/news/eu-parliament-adopts-regulation-targeting-internet-giants/ |url-status=live }}</ref> The approved text became the Parliament's mandate for negotiations with the council, which started under the [[Presidency of the Council of the European Union|French presidency of the Council]] in the first half of 2022.<ref name=":35">{{Cite web |date=2021-11-23 |title=Digital Markets Act: ending unfair practices of big online platforms |url=https://www.europarl.europa.eu/news/en/press-room/20211118IPR17636/digital-markets-act-ending-unfair-practices-of-big-online-platforms/ |access-date=2021-12-07 |language=en-GB |archive-date=7 December 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211207220524/https://www.europarl.europa.eu/news/en/press-room/20211118IPR17636/digital-markets-act-ending-unfair-practices-of-big-online-platforms/ |url-status=live }}</ref> On 25 November 2021, the Council agreed its negotiating position, providing the Presidency with a mandate for the discussions.<ref name=":36">{{Cite web |date=2021-11-25 |title=Regulating 'big tech': Council agrees on enhancing competition in the digital sphere |url=https://www.consilium.europa.eu/en/press/press-releases/2021/11/25/regulating-big-tech-council-agrees-on-enhancing-competition-in-the-digital-sphere/ |access-date=2021-12-07 |publisher=Council of the European Union |language=en-GB |archive-date=7 December 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211207221101/https://www.consilium.europa.eu/en/press/press-releases/2021/11/25/regulating-big-tech-council-agrees-on-enhancing-competition-in-the-digital-sphere// |url-status=live }}</ref>

On 24 March 2022, the Parliament and the Council meeting in the [[Formal trilogue meeting|trilogue]] format together with the Commission reached a political agreement on the DMA.<ref>{{cite web |last=Satariano |first=Adam |date=March 24, 2022 |title=E.U. Takes Aim at Big Tech's Power With Landmark Digital Act |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2022/03/24/technology/eu-regulation-apple-meta-google.html |access-date=March 24, 2022 |work=[[The New York Times]] |archive-date=4 June 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220604195224/https://www.nytimes.com/2022/03/24/technology/eu-regulation-apple-meta-google.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=":1">{{cite web |last=Bell |first=Karissa |date=March 24, 2022 |title=European Union reaches provisional agreement on antitrust law targeting tech giants |url=https://www.engadget.com/europe-digital-markets-act-005742387.html |access-date=March 24, 2022 |work=[[Engadget]] |archive-date=14 May 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220514133700/https://www.engadget.com/europe-digital-markets-act-005742387.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=":37">{{Cite web |date=2022-03-31 |title=Digital Markets Act Now Firmly on its Way |url=https://www.jdsupra.com/legalnews/digital-markets-act-now-firmly-on-its-7932391/ |access-date=2022-04-01 |language=en-GB |archive-date=1 April 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220401122950/https://www.jdsupra.com/legalnews/digital-markets-act-now-firmly-on-its-7932391/ |url-status=live }}</ref> The negotiators reached a consensus on the interoperability provisions for large messaging platforms: the said obligations will make it possible for users to communicate between different platforms, giving them more choice against the increasing dominance of certain companies.<ref name="europarl.europa.eu">{{Cite web |date=2022-03-24 |title=Deal on Digital Markets Act: ensuring fair competition and more choice for users {{!}} News {{!}} European Parliament |url=https://www.europarl.europa.eu/news/en/press-room/20220315IPR25504/deal-on-digital-markets-act-ensuring-fair-competition-and-more-choice-for-users |access-date=2022-04-20 |website=www.europarl.europa.eu |language=en |archive-date=22 April 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220422193742/https://www.europarl.europa.eu/news/en/press-room/20220315IPR25504/deal-on-digital-markets-act-ensuring-fair-competition-and-more-choice-for-users |url-status=live }}</ref> The choice is expanded also through provisions that guarantee users' free choice as regards browsers, virtual assistants or search engines, while no interoperability obligation for social networks has been decided upon yet.<ref name="europarl.europa.eu" /> In the political agreement, platforms with a market capitalization of €75 billion or turnover in the [[European Economic Area]] equal to or above €7.5 billion have been included in the rules' scope.<ref name="politico.eu">{{Cite web |date=2022-03-24 |title=EU negotiators agree new rules to rein in tech giants |url=https://www.politico.eu/article/eus-digital-markets-act-adopted/ |access-date=2022-04-20 |website=POLITICO |language=en-US |archive-date=20 April 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220420044045/https://www.politico.eu/article/eus-digital-markets-act-adopted/ |url-status=live }}</ref> An agreement was reached for penalties, which will be amounting from 10% of annual worldwide turnover due to non-compliance for first infringements up to 20% in the case of repeated infringements.<ref name="politico.eu" /> The text of the DMA provisionally agreed in March 2022 was made publicly available by the European institutions only on 22 May 2022.<ref name=":38">{{Cite web |date=2022-03-25 |title=Digital Markets Act (DMA): agreement between the Council and the European Parliament |url=https://www.consilium.europa.eu/en/press/press-releases/2022/03/25/council-and-european-parliament-reach-agreement-on-the-digital-markets-act/ |access-date=2022-05-25 |website=European Council |language=en-US |archive-date=25 May 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220525101345/https://www.consilium.europa.eu/en/press/press-releases/2022/03/25/council-and-european-parliament-reach-agreement-on-the-digital-markets-act/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

The DMA was formally adopted by the Parliament on 5 July 2022<ref>{{Cite web |date=2022-05-07 |title=Digital Services: landmark rules adopted for a safer, open online environment |url=https://www.europarl.europa.eu/news/en/press-room/20220701IPR34364/digital-services-landmark-rules-adopted-for-a-safer-open-online-environment |access-date=2022-10-13 |website=www.europarl.europa.eu |publisher=[[European Parliament]] |language=en |archive-date=16 October 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221016171724/https://www.europarl.europa.eu/news/en/press-room/20220701IPR34364/digital-services-landmark-rules-adopted-for-a-safer-open-online-environment |url-status=live }}</ref> and by the council on 19 July 2022,<ref name=":4">{{cite press release |date=19 July 2022 |title=DMA: Council gives final approval to new rules for fair competition online |url=https://www.consilium.europa.eu/en/press/press-releases/2022/07/18/dma-council-gives-final-approval-to-new-rules-for-fair-competition-online/ |publisher=[[Council of the European Union]] |language=en |access-date=19 July 2022 |archive-date=19 July 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220719154508/https://www.consilium.europa.eu/en/press/press-releases/2022/07/18/dma-council-gives-final-approval-to-new-rules-for-fair-competition-online/ |url-status=live }}</ref> and it was signed into law on 14 September 2022 by Presidents of the [[President of the European Parliament|Parliament]] and the [[Presidency of the Council of the European Union|Council]], which concluded the legislative procedure.<ref>{{cite web |author=IMCO Committee Press |date=14 September 2022 |title=#DMA is now officially signed into law |url=https://twitter.com/EP_SingleMarket/status/1570062248961363969 |access-date=15 September 2022 |archive-date=7 October 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221007214714/https://twitter.com/EP_SingleMarket/status/1570062248961363969 |url-status=live }}</ref> The adopted text was published in the [[Official Journal of the European Union]] on 12 October 2022, setting it to come into force twenty days after the publication, on 1 November 2022.<ref name=":33" />

The 2 May 2023, 6 months later, the regulation started applying and the potential gatekeepers had 2 months to report to the commission to be identified as gatekeepers. This process would take up to 45 days and after being identified as gatekeepers, they would have 6 months to come into compliance, at the latest the 6 March 2024.<ref name=":39" /><ref>{{Cite web |title=Digital Markets Act |url=https://digital-markets-act.ec.europa.eu/index_en |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230512062039/https://digital-markets-act.ec.europa.eu/index_en |archive-date=2023-05-12 |access-date=2023-05-20 |website=European Commission}}</ref> From 7 March 2024, gatekeepers must comply with the DMA.<ref>{{cite web |title=Designated gatekeepers must now comply with all obligations under the Digital Markets Act |url=https://digital-markets-act.ec.europa.eu/designated-gatekeepers-must-now-comply-all-obligations-under-digital-markets-act-2024-03-07_en |website=European Commission |access-date=16 September 2024 |language=en |date=7 March 2024}}</ref>

== Objective ==
The DMA specifically targets [[Big Tech]] companies.<ref name="auto1"/>
The DMA proposed to classify certain platforms, according to their number of users, capitalisation, market power or turnover, probably including [[Apple Inc.|Apple]], [[Google]], [[Facebook]] and [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]] as "Gatekeepers" making them subject to new obligations.<ref>{{cite magazine | url= https://www.bloomberg.com/opinion/articles/2020-12-16/europe-gets-ready-to-regulate-big-tech-giants-google-facebook-amazon-apple | title= Google, Amazon and Apple Face the Nuclear Option | last= Webb | first= Alex |magazine= [[Bloomberg News]] | date= December 16, 2020 | access-date= December 29, 2020 | archive-date= 21 December 2020 | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20201221150759/https://www.bloomberg.com/opinion/articles/2020-12-16/europe-gets-ready-to-regulate-big-tech-giants-google-facebook-amazon-apple | url-status= live }}.</ref>

It aims at preventing large companies from abusing their market power and to allow smaller and new players to enter the market.<ref name="auto"/>

Critics have suggested that with six of the gatekeepers American and one Chinese, the DMA has been constructed to deliberately target US companies.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Chee |first=Foo Yun |date=2025-02-23 |title=US demands EU antitrust chief clarify rules reining in Big Tech |url=https://www.reuters.com/technology/us-demands-eu-antitrust-chief-clarify-rules-reining-big-tech-2025-02-23/ |access-date=2025-08-29 |work=Reuters |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite report |url=https://itif.org/publications/2025/03/21/does-the-dma-intentionally-target-us-companies/ |title=Does the DMA Intentionally Target US Companies? |last=Kiss |first=Lilla Nóra |date=2025-03-21 |language=en}}</ref> The European Commission's technology and competition chiefs have responded that it is "not designed to target companies based on nationality".<ref>{{Cite web |date=2025-03-07 |title=EU tech chiefs say they don’t target US tech |url=https://www.politico.eu/article/eu-tech-chiefs-say-they-dont-target-us-tech/ |access-date=2025-08-29 |website=POLITICO |language=en-GB}}</ref>

=== Rationale ===
In December 2020, the European Commission released a legislative proposal that intends to protect consumer welfare and to restore a level playing field in the European Union's digital market.<ref name=":13">{{Cite web|last=Anderson |first=Mariniello|date=16 February 2021|title=Regulating big tech: the Digital Markets Act|url=https://www.bruegel.org/2021/02/regulating-big-tech-the-digital-markets-act/|url-status=live|website=Bruegel|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210216113153/https://www.bruegel.org/2021/02/regulating-big-tech-the-digital-markets-act/ |archive-date=16 February 2021 }}</ref> At the moment, the economy is being driven to a large extent by the activities conducted through online platforms. A small number of online platforms have come to play a crucial role in the lives of millions of individuals and companies. They intermediate a significant portion of transactions between consumers and businesses, leading to extreme dependencies of many businesses on these important platforms.<ref name=":2">{{Cite web|publisher=European Commission|date=16 December 2020|title=Inception impact assessment on the Ex ante regulatory instrument|url=https://digital-strategy.ec.europa.eu/en/library/impact-assessment-digital-markets-act|url-status=live
|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210419012012/https://digital-strategy.ec.europa.eu/en/library/impact-assessment-digital-markets-act |archive-date=19 April 2021 }}</ref>

