=== Obligations of gatekeepers ===
{{over-quotation|section|date=April 2022}}
* It may prevent practices known as self-preferencing,<ref name="auto"/> applied by companies like [[Google]] for better displaying their products among the results of Google search.
* Gatekeeper companies could also be prohibited from reusing people's personal data. For example, [[Facebook]] could be forbidden from using the data obtained from its subsidiary [[WhatsApp]].<ref>{{cite web|date=December 18, 2020|title=The EU's attempt to regulate Big Tech: What it brings and what is missing|url=https://edri.org/our-work/eu-attempt-to-regulate-big-tech/|publisher=[[European Digital Rights]] (EDRi)|access-date=December 29, 2020|archive-date=16 April 2021|archive-url=https://archive.today/20210416193315/https://edri.org/our-work/eu-attempt-to-regulate-big-tech/|url-status=live}}</ref>
* The proposal ensures rights to the platform's business users.<ref name=":02"/> For example, it could prohibit Apple from imposing a 30% commission on all the transactions concluded via App Store.
* Gatekeepers platforms may also be prohibited from requiring business users to offer their best deals on the platform (for example Amazon required e-book publishers to apply their best conditions on the Amazon e-book marketplace).<ref name=":02"/>
* There are also [[device neutrality]] rules regarding the rights to delete pre-installed applications (as in the case of Apple iOS or Google Android for example) and to install apps from other sources.<ref name=":02"/>
* Protection rights for business users of platforms (including advertisers and publishers).<ref name=":02"/>
* Prohibition of some [[Product bundling|bundling]] practices.<ref name=":02"/>
* Provisions for ensuring a higher degree of data portability, interoperability, and access to data for the platform's business and end-users.<ref name=":02"/>
* Companies that do not comply with the new obligations may risk fines up to 10% on their worldwide turnover.<ref name=":26">{{cite news|last=Sánchez Nicolás|first=Elena|date=December 16, 2020|title=Online giants could face 10% fines under new EU law|url=https://euobserver.com/science/150396|work=[[EUobserver]]|access-date=December 29, 2020|archive-date=19 December 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201219013541/https://euobserver.com/science/150396|url-status=live}}</ref>

The two following sections detail each rule individually and mention, when it is the case, the concrete example that determined the commission to include them.

==== Forbidden actions ====
This list comprises seven obligations and prohibitions for addressing the unfair trading practices. All the identified gatekeepers will have to respect these provisions:<ref name=":11" />

{{blockquote|(a) Prevents Gatekeepers to combine personal data coming from Core Platforms Services (CPS) with data collected through other services of the same Gatekeepers or from a third party. Also, it prevents end-users being signed-in to other services offered by the Gatekeepers. However, this can be done only if the choice has been presented to the end-user and consent given.<ref name=":11" /><ref name=":3"/>}}

Combining personal data from different sources was ruled illegal by the German [[Federal Cartel Office]] in 2019, in a case against Facebook.<ref name=":02"/> The company was also fined €110 million in May 2017 for notifying the Commission that it would not be possible to combine data coming from Facebook and WhatsApp, at the time of the acquisition of WhatsApp in 2014. However, the Commission found that this practice constituted a possibility since 2014, given the fact that WhatsApp inserted this option in its terms of services [[privacy policy]] in 2016.<ref name=":30">{{Cite news|last=Murgia|first=Madhumita|date=18 May 2017|title=Facebook fined €110m by European Commission over WhatsApp deal|url=https://www.ft.com/content/a2dadc48-3bb1-11e7-821a-6027b8a20f23|url-status=live|access-date=2021-04-23|newspaper=Financial Times|archive-date=21 May 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170521054619/https://www.ft.com/content/a2dadc48-3bb1-11e7-821a-6027b8a20f23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|last=European Commission|date=18 May 2017|title=Mergers: Commission fines Facebook €110 million for providing misleading information about WhatsApp takeover|url=https://ec.europa.eu/commission/presscorner/home/en|url-status=live|access-date=2021-04-23|publisher=European Commission|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190621200951/https://ec.europa.eu/commission/presscorner/home/en |archive-date=21 June 2019 }}</ref>

{{blockquote|(b) allow business users to offer the same products or services to end-users through third party online intermediation services at prices or conditions that are different from those offered through the online intermediation services of the Gatekeeper.<ref name=":11" />}}

This has already been considered illegal in a competition law-case concerning Amazon e-books. In its contracts with the publishers of E-books, Amazon required them to offer at least the best price or conditions that they proposed to any other competitors.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Toplensky|first=Rochelle|date=2017-05-04|title=Brussels ends Amazon e-books probe|url=https://www.ft.com/content/61c92a63-2e35-3739-9ed7-c190c2775cd4|access-date=2021-04-23|newspaper=Financial Times|archive-date=23 April 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210423205032/https://www.ft.com/content/61c92a63-2e35-3739-9ed7-c190c2775cd4|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|author=<!-- Staff writer(s); no by-line -->|date=2017-05-04|title=EU accepts Amazon e-book commitments to settle antitrust case|language=en|work=Reuters|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-eu-amazon-com-antitrust-idUSKBN180119|access-date=2021-04-23|archive-date=23 April 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210423205030/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-eu-amazon-com-antitrust-idUSKBN180119|url-status=live}}</ref> This article also derives from the cases concerning online travel agencies such as [[Booking.com]] or [[Expedia]].<ref name=":02"/><ref>{{Cite web|last=Solek|first=Lukas|date=14 November 2019|title=Price Parity Clauses and Online Platforms: Is There a New Way Forward? |url=https://www.linklaters.com/en/insights/blogs/linkingcompetition/2019/november/price-parity-clauses-and-online-platforms-is-there-a-new-way-forward|url-status=live|access-date=2021-04-23|publisher=Linklaters|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200421143551/https://www.linklaters.com/en/insights/blogs/linkingcompetition/2019/november/price-parity-clauses-and-online-platforms-is-there-a-new-way-forward |archive-date=21 April 2020 }}</ref>

{{blockquote|(c) allow business users to promote offers to end users acquired via the core platform service, and to conclude contracts with these end users regardless of whether for that purpose they use the core platform services of the gatekeeper or not, allow end users to access and use, through the core platform services of the gatekeeper, content, subscriptions, features or other items by using the software application of a business user, where these items have been acquired by the end users from the relevant business user without using the core platform services of the gatekeeper <ref name=":11" />}}

The legal character of this kind of practices is currently investigated by the European Commission in a case concerning the App Store of Apple and the 30% commission that they charged to all the subscriptions made through the App Store.<ref name=":27">{{Cite news|last=Espinoza|first=Javier|date=16 June 2020|title=Apple faces twin antitrust probes in Brussels|url=https://www.ft.com/content/9c847838-ca25-43cf-a962-0d3588d8d34d|url-status=live|access-date=2021-04-23|newspaper=Financial Times|archive-date=23 April 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210423205031/https://www.ft.com/content/9c847838-ca25-43cf-a962-0d3588d8d34d}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Espinoza|first=Javier|date=4 March 2021|title=EU to charge Apple with antitrust abuse for first time|url=https://www.ft.com/content/d37c476c-b4cd-4b47-9ed2-d19ad2341ea8|url-status=live|access-date=2021-04-23|newspaper=Financial Times|archive-date=23 April 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210423205030/https://www.ft.com/content/d37c476c-b4cd-4b47-9ed2-d19ad2341ea8}}</ref><ref name=":28">{{Cite web|date=16 June 2020|title=Antitrust: Commission opens investigations into Apple's App Store rules|url=https://ec.europa.eu/commission/presscorner/home/en|url-status=live|access-date=2021-04-23|publisher=European Commission|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190621200951/https://ec.europa.eu/commission/presscorner/home/en |archive-date=21 June 2019 }}</ref>

{{blockquote|(d) refrain from preventing or restricting business users from raising issues with any relevant public authority relating to any practice of gatekeepers<ref name=":11" />}}

This is a general practice that does not come from the case law but it guarantees the right of business-users to raise possible concerns to public authorities (such as the European Commission).<ref name=":02"/>

{{blockquote|(e) refrain from requiring business users to use, offer or interoperate with an identification service of the gatekeeper in the context of services offered by the business users using the core platform services of that gatekeeper.<ref name=":11" />}}

Also known as a ''[[Product bundling|bundling]]'' practice, it prevents gatekeepers from forcing business users to use the ID of the Core Platform Services when they offer their services. Thus, it is often related to advertisers or publishers issues such as Google and their methods of collecting data.<ref name="Chee">{{Cite news|last=Chee|first=Foo Yun|date=2021-01-20|title=Google's advertising practices targeted by EU antitrust probe|language=en|work=Reuters|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-google-antitrust-eu-idUSKBN29P23U|access-date=2021-04-23|archive-date=23 April 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210423205040/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-google-antitrust-eu-idUSKBN29P23U|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|last1=Larger |first1=Thibaut |last2=Kayali |first2=Laura|date=2021-01-19|title=Brussels zeroes in on Google's adtech business|url=https://www.politico.eu/article/brussels-zeroes-in-on-googles-data/|url-status=live|access-date=2021-04-23|website=Politico|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210119133556/https://www.politico.eu/article/brussels-zeroes-in-on-googles-data/ |archive-date=19 January 2021 }}</ref><ref name=":02"/>

{{blockquote|(f) Prevents the bundling of different CPSs of the platform that are identified as gatekeeper.<ref name=":11" />}}

For this bundling practice, in 2018, Google was fined with €4.3 billion by the Commission in a decision on Android.<ref name=":23">{{Cite web|date=18 July 2018|title=Antitrust: Commission fines Google €4.34 billion for illegal practices regarding Android mobile devices to strengthen dominance of Google's search engine|url=https://ec.europa.eu/commission/presscorner/home/en|url-status=live|access-date=2021-04-23|publisher=European Commission|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190621200951/https://ec.europa.eu/commission/presscorner/home/en |archive-date=21 June 2019 }}</ref> The company breached the antitrust rules of the EU by forcing Android's users to pre-install its own services, such as Google search and Google Chrome.<ref name=":31">{{Cite news|last1=Satariano|first1=Adam|last2=Nicas|first2=Jack|date=2018-07-18|title=E.U. Fines Google $5.1 Billion in Android Antitrust Case|work=The New York Times|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/07/18/technology/google-eu-android-fine.html|access-date=2021-04-23|issn=0362-4331|archive-date=22 October 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221022174422/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/07/18/technology/google-eu-android-fine.html|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|last=Rankin|first=Jennifer|date=2018-07-18|title=Google fined £3.8bn by EU over Android antitrust violations|url=http://www.theguardian.com/business/2018/jul/18/google-faces-record-multibillion-fine-from-eu-over-android|url-status=live|access-date=2021-04-23|website=The Guardian|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180718101830/https://www.theguardian.com/business/2018/jul/18/google-faces-record-multibillion-fine-from-eu-over-android |archive-date=18 July 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last1=Barker|first1=Alex|last2=Khan|first2=Mehreen|date=18 July 2018|title=EU fines Google record €4.3bn over Android|url=https://www.ft.com/content/56ae8282-89d7-11e8-b18d-0181731a0340|url-status=live|access-date=2021-04-23|newspaper=Financial Times|archive-date=23 April 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210423205031/https://www.ft.com/content/56ae8282-89d7-11e8-b18d-0181731a0340}}</ref> This way, Google secured its dominant position in terms of internet search.<ref name=":23" />

{{blockquote|(g) provide advertisers and publishers to which it supplies advertising services, upon their request, with information concerning the price paid by the advertiser and publisher, as well as the amount or remuneration paid to the publisher, for the publishing of a given ad and for each of the relevant advertising services provided by the gatekeeper}}

This last obligation is linked to the investigation of the European Commission on Google's data and advertising practices.<ref name="Chee"/><ref>{{Cite news|last=White|first=Aoife|date=2021-01-19|title=Google Back in EU Crosshairs as Regulators Probe Ad Tech Moves|language=en|work=Bloomberg|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2021-01-19/google-back-in-eu-crosshairs-as-regulators-probe-ad-tech-moves|access-date=2021-04-23|archive-date=23 April 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210423205031/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2021-01-19/google-back-in-eu-crosshairs-as-regulators-probe-ad-tech-moves|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=":02"/>

==== Case by case assessment ====
Article 6 of the DMA contains a second list of eleven obligations and prohibitions for gatekeepers. These obligations are specified individually by the European Commission after consulting the gatekeepers concerned.

{{blockquote|(a) refrain from using, in competition with business users, any data not publicly available, which is generated through activities by those business users, including by the end users of these business users, of its core platform services or provided by those business users of its core platform services or by the end users of these business users<ref name=":11" />}}

The potential ban of this practice derives from the Amazon Marketplace case that is under investigation by the European Commission.<ref name=":29">{{Cite web|date=10 November 2020|title=Antitrust: Commission sends Statement of Objections to Amazon for the use of non-public independent seller data and opens second investigation into its e-commerce business practices|url=https://ec.europa.eu/commission/presscorner/home/en|url-status=live|access-date=2021-04-24|website=European Commission|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190621200951/https://ec.europa.eu/commission/presscorner/home/en |archive-date=21 June 2019 }}</ref> The Commission claimed that Amazon breached antitrust rules by using "non-public data" from their business users in order to compete with them.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Espinoza|first=Javier|date=10 November 2020|title=EU accuses Amazon of breaching antitrust rules|url=https://www.ft.com/content/4908995d-5ba4-4e14-a863-bcb8858e8bd2|url-status=live|access-date=2021-04-24|newspaper=Financial Times|archive-date=24 April 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210424015509/https://www.ft.com/content/4908995d-5ba4-4e14-a863-bcb8858e8bd2}}</ref><ref name=":29"/>

{{blockquote|(b) To guarantee the possibility for end-users to uninstall pre-installed applications on its CPS.<ref name=":11" />}}

This obligation derives from the cases on Microsoft Internet Explorer<!-- not Explorer, the file manager --> and Google Android, where the European Commission forced them to allow end-users to uninstall pre-installed app from their core platforms services.<ref name=":02"/><ref>{{Cite news|last=Tait|first=Nikki|date=8 October 2009|title=Microsoft close to EU deal on browser dispute|url=https://www.ft.com/content/98d841d6-b333-11de-ac13-00144feab49a|url-status=live|access-date=2021-04-24|newspaper=Financial Times|archive-date=24 April 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210424015512/https://www.ft.com/content/98d841d6-b333-11de-ac13-00144feab49a}}</ref><ref name=":23" />

{{blockquote|(c) allow the installation and effective use of third party software applications or software application stores using, or interoperating with, operating systems of that gatekeeper and allow these software applications or software application stores to be accessed by means other than the core platform services of that gatekeeper<ref name=":11" />}}

The practice is currently investigated in the ''Apple App Store case''. The Commission considers that Apple does not let its competitors inform users about the possibility to buy their products on other platforms than the App store, at potential cheaper prices.<ref name=":27"/><ref name=":28"/>

{{blockquote|(d) refrain from treating more favourably in ranking services and products offered by the gatekeeper itself or by any third party belonging to the same undertaking compared to similar services or products of third party and apply fair and non discriminatory conditions to such ranking<ref name=":11" />}}

This practice has already been prohibited in the case of ''Google Shopping'' and is currently investigated in the ''Amazon Buy Box'' case.<ref name=":3"/> Mainly, it refers to self-preferencing own products at the expense of competitors in the search results of a certain marketplace.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Espinoza|first=Javier|date=12 February 2020|title=Google and EU battle in court over €2.4bn fine|url=https://www.ft.com/content/6ec3f6a6-4d56-11ea-95a0-43d18ec715f5|url-status=live|access-date=2021-04-24|newspaper=Financial Times|archive-date=24 April 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210424015510/https://www.ft.com/content/6ec3f6a6-4d56-11ea-95a0-43d18ec715f5}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|last=Scott |first=Mark|date=2020-11-10|title=EU charges Amazon with misusing data, opens new probe over Buy Box|url=https://www.politico.eu/article/amazon-antitrust-europe-margrethe-vestager/|url-status=live|access-date=2021-04-24|website=Politico|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201110110921/https://www.politico.eu/article/amazon-antitrust-europe-margrethe-vestager/ |archive-date=10 November 2020 }}</ref>

{{blockquote|(e) refrain from technically restricting the ability of end users to switch between and subscribe to different software applications and services to be accessed using the operating system of the gatekeeper...<ref name=":11" />}}

This can be seen as deriving from the conflict between Spotify and Apple on the restrictions imposed to use Spotify on Apple devices, that had the purpose of promoting Apple music services.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Chee|first=Foo Yun|date=2021-03-04|title=Exclusive: Apple faces EU charges over Spotify complaint – sources|work=Reuters|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-eu-apple-antitrust-exclusive-idUSKBN2AW24K|access-date=2021-04-24|archive-date=24 April 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210424050318/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-eu-apple-antitrust-exclusive-idUSKBN2AW24K|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=":02"/>

{{blockquote|(f) allow business users and providers of ancillary services access to and interoperability with the same operating system, hardware or software features that are available or used in the provision by the gatekeeper of any ancillary services<ref name=":11" />}}

[[File:Comunicação entre back-end e front-end em sistemas web.png|thumb|Interoperability: Application programming interface (API) allow to connect providers of ancillary services to the operating system, hardware or software of gatekeepers, they can enable interoperability as required by the DMA]]
This provision can be illustrated for example by practices currently analysed in the ''Apple Pay case.'' By favouring its devices and its own method of payment – [[Apple Pay]] – at the expense of its competitors, Apple is currently scrutinized by the commission.<ref>{{Cite news|last=McGee|first=Patrick|date=16 October 2019|title=EU sets sights on Apple Pay over antitrust concerns|url=https://www.ft.com/content/e65c9a76-f039-11e9-bfa4-b25f11f42901|url-status=live|access-date=2021-04-24|newspaper=Financial Times|archive-date=25 February 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210225232144/https://www.ft.com/content/e65c9a76-f039-11e9-bfa4-b25f11f42901}}</ref>
Interoperability requirement is a key demand by civil society and the [[open source]] community.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ianbrown.tech/digital-competition-briefing-1/european-union/ |title=Data protection and digital competition|last1=  Brown|first1=Ian |last2=Korff |first2=Douwe|date=30 December 2022 |website= |publisher= |access-date=9 October 2023 |quote=}}</ref>

{{blockquote|(g) provide advertisers and publishers, upon their request and free of charge, with access to the performance measuring tools of the gatekeeper and the information necessary for advertisers and publishers to carry out their own  independent verification of the ad inventory<ref name=":11" />}}

This article would help business users of platforms, especially advertisers, to have access to the data related to the ads and publications posted on the Gatekeeper's platforms. Facebook and Google are potentially the main targets of this article, and maybe Amazon.<ref name=":02"/>

{{blockquote|(h) provide effective portability of data generated through the activity of a business user or end user and shall, in particular, provide tools for end users to facilitate the exercise of data portability, in line with [[General Data Protection Regulation|GDPR]] (Regulation EU 2016/679), including by the provision of continuous and real-time access<ref name=":11" />}}

The abovementioned provision has a more general scope and it is not built around specific cases. Seen as complementing the [[General Data Protection Regulation|GDPR]] regulation, it gives more precision regarding the scope of [[data portability]], by adding that the data access should be "continuous" and "real time". In practical terms, this guarantees both access to users (including business-users) and benefits in terms of up-to-date data portability generated by the platform.

{{blockquote|(i) provide business users, or third parties authorised by a business user, free of charge, with effective, high-quality, continuous and real-time access and use of aggregated or non-aggregated data, that is provided for or generated in the context of the use of the relevant core platform services by those business users and the end users engaging with the products or services provided by those business users; for personal data, provide access and use only where directly connected with the use effectuated by the end user in respect of the products or services offered by the relevant business user through the relevant core platform service, and when the end user opts in to such sharing with a consent in the sense of the  [[General Data Protection Regulation|GDPR Regulation (EU) 2016/679]];<ref name=":11" />}}

As article (h), this article does not derive from an individual case and complements the GDPR.<ref name=":02"/> It guarantees more rights to business and end-users regarding the [[interoperability]] of the data generated on platforms.<ref name=":02"/> This is meant to make data generated by different platforms compatible and usable by different systems.<ref>{{Cite web|last=DISC|title=What is 'Data Interoperability'?|url=https://datainteroperability.org/|url-status=live|access-date=2021-04-27|website=The Data Interoperability Standards Consortium|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160131005909/http://datainteroperability.org:80/ |archive-date=31 January 2016 }}</ref>

{{blockquote|(j) provide to any third party providers of online search engines, upon their request, with access on fair, reasonable and non-discriminatory terms to ranking, query, click and view data in relation to free and paid search generated by end users on online search engines of the gatekeeper, subject to anonymisation for the query, click and view data that constitutes personal data;<ref name=":11" />}}

This article is especially meant to ensure a higher degree of competition in the online search engines market, by providing more rights to the (new) competitors.<ref name=":02"/> It gives providers of online search engines access to data generated by the Gatekeeper in the sector (presumably Google Search at the moment, as it concentrates 95% of the market share in this sector).<ref name=":2"/> This is also related to the ''Google Search'' case and to Article 5(d) or the "blacklisted actions" of the DMA (see above).<ref name=":02"/>

{{blockquote|(k) apply fair and non-discriminatory general conditions of access for business users to its software application store&nbsp;...<ref name=":11" />}}

This provision targets the store application of Gatekeepers ([[App Store (iOS/iPadOS)|App Store]], [[Google Play]]),<ref name=":02"/> and has the aim to protect the rights of app developers and of business-users.

=== Other obligations for gatekeepers ===
* Under Art. 12, Gatekeepers have to notify the Commission their intended future merger and acquisition.
* Under Art. 3, Gatekeepers have to notify the Commission when they meet the thresholds to be considered as gatekeepers (see above the section related to the criteria).
* Under Art. 13, when designated as gatekeepers, the firm has to conduct an independent audit about their profiling technique of consumers and submit it to the commission.

=== European Commission's investigation powers and sanctions mechanisms ===
The Digital Markets Act will allow the European Commission to have regulatory and market investigation powers. Under these circumstances, market investigations will be mainly designated to:<ref name=":11" />
* Conduct markets investigation so as to specify the obligations imposed on Gatekeepers and monitor compliance (Art. 16)
* Conduct markets investigation in order to designate gatekeepers (Art. 15)
* Conduct market investigations to identify new services and practices that can be subject to the obligations listed in Art. 5 and Art. 6 (Art. 17)
* Chapter V of the proposal gives the commission a certain number of rights in order to conduct these investigations
* Sanctions for gatekeepers in case of non-compliance or systematic non-compliance are represented by fines up to 10% of the Gatekeeper's worldwide turnover.<ref name=":26"/><ref name=":11" />

=== Relationship to national competition law enforcement ===
Art. 1(5) of the Digital Markets Act states that Member States are prohibited from imposing on gatekeepers further obligations by way of laws, regulations or administrative action for the purpose of ensuring contestable and fair markets. Obligations that are unrelated to the relevant undertakings having a status of gatekeeper within the meaning of the Digital Markets Act are exempted from this prohibition.<ref>[https://ec.europa.eu/info/sites/default/files/proposal-regulation-single-market-digital-services-digital-services-act_en.pdf Digital services act] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220324043740/https://ec.europa.eu/info/sites/default/files/proposal-regulation-single-market-digital-services-digital-services-act_en.pdf |date=24 March 2022 }}</ref>

On 22 March 2022, the European Court of Justice ruled in the joint cases C-117/20 Bpost and C-151/20 Nordzucker that investigators can start antitrust scrutiny of companies that have already been probed under sector regulation such as the Digital Markets Act, so long as the two cases are "conducted in a sufficiently coordinated manner within a proximate timeframe and the overall penalties imposed must correspond to the seriousness of the offenses committed."<ref>{{Cite web |title=MLex {{!}} Insight and Comment on Regulatory Risk for Law Firms, Corporations and Hedge Funds |url=https://content.mlex.com/#/content/1366731 |access-date=2022-04-12 |website=content.mlex.com |archive-date=12 April 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220412130421/https://content.mlex.com/#/content/1366731 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=MLex {{!}} Insight and Comment on Regulatory Risk for Law Firms, Corporations and Hedge Funds |url=https://content.mlex.com/#/content/1366732?referrer=content_seehereview |access-date=2022-04-12 |website=content.mlex.com |archive-date=12 April 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220412130421/https://content.mlex.com/#/content/1366732?referrer=content_seehereview |url-status=live }}</ref>

This opens up a path for parallel national prosecution of gatekeepers, for example as Germany has done under the German competition law amendment Section 19a.<ref>[https://www.politico.eu/wp-content/uploads/2021/01/13/German-Competition-Law-Reform-Compromise-Draft.pdf German competition law] politico.eu 13 January 2021 {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220412110307/https://www.politico.eu/wp-content/uploads/2021/01/13/German-Competition-Law-Reform-Compromise-Draft.pdf |date=12 April 2022 }}</ref> The German Federal Cartel Office has in 2021 opened multiple proceedings against large tech firms that would be considered gatekeepers under the Digital Markets Act, including Facebook (now: Meta),<ref>{{Cite web |title=Bundeskartellamt - Homepage - First proceeding based on new rules for digital companies – Bundeskartellamt also assesses new Section 19a GWB in its Facebook/Oculus case |url=https://www.bundeskartellamt.de/SharedDocs/Meldung/EN/Pressemitteilungen/2021/28_01_2021_Facebook_Oculus.html;jsessionid=7ABDE3247F5B77EFAF1F20882632900E.1_cid362?nn=3591568 |access-date=2022-04-12 |website=www.bundeskartellamt.de |archive-date=12 April 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220412110316/https://www.bundeskartellamt.de/SharedDocs/Meldung/EN/Pressemitteilungen/2021/28_01_2021_Facebook_Oculus.html;jsessionid=7ABDE3247F5B77EFAF1F20882632900E.1_cid362?nn=3591568 |url-status=live }}</ref> Amazon,<ref>{{Cite web |title=Bundeskartellamt - Homepage - Proceedings against Amazon based on new rules for large digital companies (Section 19a GWB) |url=https://www.bundeskartellamt.de/SharedDocs/Meldung/EN/Pressemitteilungen/2021/18_05_2021_Amazon_19a.html?nn=3591568 |access-date=2022-04-12 |website=www.bundeskartellamt.de |archive-date=12 April 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220412110320/https://www.bundeskartellamt.de/SharedDocs/Meldung/EN/Pressemitteilungen/2021/18_05_2021_Amazon_19a.html?nn=3591568 |url-status=live }}</ref> Apple<ref>{{Cite web |title=Bundeskartellamt - Homepage - Proceeding against Apple based on new rules for large digital companies (Section 19a(1) GWB) – Bundeskartellamt examines Apple's significance for competition across markets |url=https://www.bundeskartellamt.de/SharedDocs/Meldung/EN/Pressemitteilungen/2021/21_06_2021_Apple.html;jsessionid=E1E94061ED59CB03EE83AA852B574DB7.1_cid390?nn=3591568 |access-date=2022-04-12 |website=www.bundeskartellamt.de |archive-date=12 April 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220412110310/https://www.bundeskartellamt.de/SharedDocs/Meldung/EN/Pressemitteilungen/2021/21_06_2021_Apple.html;jsessionid=E1E94061ED59CB03EE83AA852B574DB7.1_cid390?nn=3591568 |url-status=live }}</ref> and Google.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Bundeskartellamt - Homepage - Proceeding against Google based on new rules for large digital players (Section 19a GWB) – Bundeskartellamt examines Google's significance for competition across markets and its data processing terms |url=https://www.bundeskartellamt.de/SharedDocs/Meldung/EN/Pressemitteilungen/2021/25_05_2021_Google_19a.html;jsessionid=13306169089CBFA2AA708D8D58DD93C0.1_cid362?nn=3591568 |access-date=2022-04-12 |website=www.bundeskartellamt.de |archive-date=12 April 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220412110313/https://www.bundeskartellamt.de/SharedDocs/Meldung/EN/Pressemitteilungen/2021/25_05_2021_Google_19a.html;jsessionid=13306169089CBFA2AA708D8D58DD93C0.1_cid362?nn=3591568 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Bundeskartellamt - Homepage - Bundeskartellamt examines Google News Showcase |url=https://www.bundeskartellamt.de/SharedDocs/Meldung/EN/Pressemitteilungen/2021/04_06_2021_Google_Showcase.html;jsessionid=B7FEA303D7958E740AF462DD18C67703.2_cid371?nn=3591568 |access-date=2022-04-12 |website=www.bundeskartellamt.de}}</ref> Section 19a cases may involve coordination among the German Federal Cartel Office and the European Commission and other national competition authorities. Legally, it has been proposed by the Federal Cartel Office that Section 19a must be seen as an expansion of competition law, meaning that it could be applied parallel to the Digital Markets Act. The trilogue negotiations on the Digital Markets Act have not yielded a common position on the matter.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2022-03-29 |title=European Union Reached a Political Agreement on the Digital Markets Act |url=https://www.huntonprivacyblog.com/2022/03/29/european-union-reached-a-political-agreement-on-the-digital-markets-act/ |access-date=2022-04-12 |website=Privacy & Information Security Law Blog |language=en-US |archive-date=29 March 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220329145629/https://www.huntonprivacyblog.com/2022/03/29/european-union-reached-a-political-agreement-on-the-digital-markets-act/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

== Identified gatekeepers ==
{{Update inline|date=June 2024|reason=The EU has added booking.com as a new gatekeeper and started investigating x.com: https://ec.europa.eu/commission/presscorner/detail/en/ip_24_2561}}

As of September 2023, the list of gatekeepers was revealed to be [[Alphabet Inc.|Alphabet]], [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]], [[Apple Inc.|Apple]], [[ByteDance]], [[Meta Platforms|Meta]] and [[Microsoft]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Lomas |first=Natasha |date=2023-09-06 |title=EU confirms six (mostly US) tech giants are subject to Digital Markets Act |url=https://techcrunch.com/2023/09/06/dma-gatekeepers-named/ |access-date=2023-09-15 |website=TechCrunch |language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Digital Markets Act: Commission designates six gatekeepers |url=https://ec.europa.eu/commission/presscorner/detail/en/ip_23_4328 |access-date=2023-09-15 |website=European Commission - European Commission |language=en}}</ref>

The twenty-two core products listed as gatekeeping products were:
* Alphabet: [[Google Search]], [[Google Maps]], [[Google Play]], [[Google Shopping]], [[Google Ads]], [[Google Chrome|Chrome]], [[Android (operating system)|Android]], [[YouTube]]
* Amazon: [[Amazon Marketplace]], [[Amazon Product Advertising]]
* Apple: [[App Store (Apple)|App Store]], [[Safari (web browser)|Safari]], [[iOS]]
* Bytedance: [[TikTok]]
* Meta: [[Facebook]], [[Instagram]], [[Facebook Marketplace]], [[WhatsApp]], [[Facebook Messenger|Messenger]]
* Microsoft: [[LinkedIn]], [[Microsoft Windows]]

=== Alphabet ===
[[Alphabet Inc.]] is the parent company of Google. Tensions between Alphabet and the European Union have been generated by sanctions applied to unfair practices related to advertising, [[mobile operating system]], or shopping strategies. Several fines were imposed by the European Commission to Alphabet because of breaches of competition law but taking into account that despite the CJEU's rulings, "inefficient market outcomes in terms of higher prices, lower quality, less choice and innovation" still emerged, the DMA aims to better regulate this area.<ref>{{Cite web |title=IMMC.SWD%282020%29364%20final.ENG.xhtml.1_EN_resume_impact_assessment_part1_v3.docx |url=https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/HTML/?uri=CELEX:52020SC0364 |access-date=2024-10-16 |website=eur-lex.europa.eu}}</ref>{{Failed verification|date=October 2024|reason=the source does not apply to Alphabet specifically}}

As the main focus of the DMA is represented by operators that provide search engines, social networks, cloud computing services and operating systems, Google was one of the companies that officially presented its position.<ref name=":5">{{Cite news|last=Kelion|first=Leo|date=15 December 2020|title=EU reveals plan to regulate Big Tech|work=BBC News|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-55318225|url-status=live|access-date=2 April 2021|archive-date=21 March 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210321200604/https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-55318225}}</ref> In an interview, Google executive Matt Brittin stated that: "It's so important to get the rules right for European consumers to have more choice, to support the kind of jobs we'll need in the future and to support European businesses."<ref name=":5"/>

Even though not specifically named, Google is one of the companies that will be affected by the stringent rules, because the legislation will be applied to firms with European revenues of at least €6.5&nbsp;bn or at least 45 million users across Europe. Nevertheless, as subject to potential fines of up to 10% of its global revenue for breaking the rules,<ref name=":6">{{Cite web|last=Clarke|first=Laurie|date=16 December 2020|title=Europe's Digital Markets Act: A shift to proactive Big Tech regulation|url=https://techmonitor.ai/boardroom/regulation-compliance/europes-digital-markets-act-shift-proactive-big-tech-regulation|url-status=live|website=Tech Monitor|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201217161638/https://techmonitor.ai/boardroom/regulation-compliance/europes-digital-markets-act-shift-proactive-big-tech-regulation |archive-date=17 December 2020 }}</ref> Google is highly incentivized to continue influencing the legislators and lobbying in Brussels for obtaining better conditions under the Digital Market Act.

The rhetoric of Google and its attempts to contour an official position relied mainly on the risks that might emerge from the legislative act, namely barriers – "as Europeans will only have access to less choice and to more costly alternatives".<ref name=":6"/> Nevertheless, the big tech has also tried to highlight the weaknesses of the Digital Market Act and they labelled it a blacklist – whose implications in terms of interoperability might not generate innovation in the future, but incentives for "lowest common denominator".<ref>{{Cite web|last=O'Dea|first=Sean|date=27 November 2020|title=What the Tech is Going on with Digital Markets and Antitrust/Competition Law?|url=https://www.mccannfitzgerald.com/knowledge/antitrust-competition/what-is-going-on-with-digital-markets-and-antitrust-competition-law|url-status=live|website=McCann FitzGerald|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210118204000/https://www.mccannfitzgerald.com/knowledge/antitrust-competition/what-is-going-on-with-digital-markets-and-antitrust-competition-law |archive-date=18 January 2021 }}</ref>

In November 2020, the French [[news magazine]] ''[[Le Point]]'' published Google's leaked lobby strategy on the Digital Market Act, thus several practices and intentions have been uncovered.<ref name=":5"/> For example, there were made references to:

{{blockquote|
* Lobby at Parliament, Commission and member state level;
* Re-frame the political narrative around costs to the economy and consumers;
* Mobilise third parties (such as think-tanks and academics) to echo Google's message;
* Mobilise the US Government;
* Create "pushback" against Commissioner Breton (who was seen as supporting potential break ups)
* Create conflict between Commission departments.<ref name=":7">{{Cite web|last=Corporate Europe Observatory|date=11 December 2020|title=Big Tech brings out the big guns in fight for future of EU tech regulation|url=https://corporateeurope.org/en/2020/12/big-tech-brings-out-big-guns-fight-future-eu-tech-regulation|url-status=live|website=Corporate Europe Observatory|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201213233635/https://corporateeurope.org/en/2020/12/big-tech-brings-out-big-guns-fight-future-eu-tech-regulation |archive-date=13 December 2020 }}</ref>{{verify source|reason=Was not formatted as a block quotation; was unclear about what was quoted|date=April 2022}}}}

As far as the cost of these lobbying practices is concerned, according to the Transparency Register, Google spent more than €19 million on lobbying in the first half of 2020.<ref name=":7"/> Even though the sum of money allocated by Google has already reached significant levels, the numbers presented above do not comprise all the transactions related to academic partnerships, law firms, or activities conducted in individual Member States.

Corporate Europe Observatory investigated the fight of EU tech regulation and according to its findings, 158 meetings were registered since the Von der Leyen Commission took office, meetings that "involved 103 organisations, mostly companies and lobby groups. Only 13 actors had at least 3 or more meetings logged on these issues. Google stands out with the most meetings with Microsoft and Facebook trailing close behind. Apple and Amazon have also lobbied on the DMA and/ or DSA, although they rank lower overall with two and one meeting respectively".<ref name=":7"/> However, one of the limitations faced is represented by the fact that the endeavours with the officials responsible for drafting the legislation are not mentioned, as only the official meetings with high representatives are declared or announced.<ref name=":7"/>

Despite the fact that the proposal has been published on 15 December 2020, the lobbying practices still represent an ongoing process because they have been transferred from the commission to the European Parliament and Council. However, comparing the data obtained on the meetings of the European Commission with the information made available by the other institutions, it can be observed that transparency is even less stringent.

In October 2023 the [[Federal Cartel Office|German cartel office]] said Alphabet unit Google had agreed to change its user data practices to end a German antitrust investigation aimed at curbing its data-driven market power.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2023-10-05 |title=Google changes user data practices to end German antitrust probe |url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/german-cartel-office-google-users-084130313.html |access-date=2023-10-05 |website=Yahoo Finance |language=en-US}}</ref>

Alphabet responded by:<ref>{{cite web | url=https://blog.google/around-the-globe/google-europe/complying-with-the-digital-markets-act/ | title=Complying with the Digital Markets Act | date=5 March 2024 }}</ref>
*Creating the Data Portability API, an API that allows to transfer content of Chrome browser, Google Maps, Play Store, Google Search, Google Shopping, and YouTube to another service, but is only available in all EEA countries only, and the United Kingdom
*Added additional data for EEA advertisers.
*Launching a program to have external payment in Google Play Store.
*[[Android 14]] supports seamless updating on third-party app stores worldwide.
*Added a settings panel to unlink data between most Google services.
*Added EU choice screens to Android, which are randomly ordered.
*Added dedicated chips to link to external services for features like flight search.
In September 2024, the [[EU Court of Justice]] found that [[Google Shopping|Google's shopping search]] was in violation of the Digital Markets Act.<ref name="europeanshopping">{{cite news |last=Hancock |first=Edith |date=September 10, 2024 |title=Google loses EU court battle over €2.4B antitrust fine |url=https://www.politico.eu/article/google-loses-court-battle-over-first-eu-antitrust-fine/ |access-date=September 10, 2024 |work=Politico}}</ref>

===Amazon===
Amazon welcomed the DMA and according to its position,<ref>{{Cite web |date=2024-03-07 |title=Amazon and the Digital Markets Act |url=https://www.aboutamazon.eu/news/policy/amazon-and-the-digital-markets-act |access-date=2024-10-27 |website=EU About Amazon |language=en}}</ref> the company has not been as concerned about it as the other GAFAM members.{{citation needed|date=October 2022}} This can be explained by the fact that compared to Google's and Apple's case, the Digital Markets Act could affect Amazon only in three aspects:{{original research inline|date=October 2022}}
* Amazon might be obliged to allow business users to offer the same products or services to end-users at prices or conditions that are different from those offered by Amazon (DMA Article 5b)
* Amazon might be obliged not to use data from competitors that is not public (DMA Article 6a)
* Amazon might be obliged not to treat the services and the products it offers more favourably (DMA Article 6d)

The prohibition on using non-public data from competitors it hosts on its platform and the prohibition on ranking its product before the ones offered by competitors may impact Amazon if the proposal for the DMA is adopted under its current form. Moreover, these aspects caused Amazon to negotiate the final version of the regulation, taking into account that it spent €1.75 million on lobbying practices and that it became a member of several think tanks.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Corporate Europe Observatory |date=23 September 2020 |title=Big Tech Lobbying Google, Amazon & friends and their hidden influence |url=https://corporateeurope.org/en/2020/09/big-tech-lobbying |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210414161824/https://corporateeurope.org/en/2020/09/big-tech-lobbying |archive-date=14 April 2021 |access-date=14 April 2021}}</ref>

===Apple===
The new European draft legislation has also targeted Apple's App Store with regard to its practices and preinstalled applications. One of the main changes that will be brought to their current [[business model]] is represented by the removal of the "self-preferencing" strategy.<ref name=":17">{{Cite web|last=Potuck|first=Michael|date=15 December 2020|title=New EU legislation targets Apple's App Store practices and preinstalled apps|url=https://9to5mac.com/2020/12/15/apple-eu-legislation-app-store-changes/|url-status=live|access-date=12 April 2021|website=9to5Mac|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201215170149/https://9to5mac.com/2020/12/15/apple-eu-legislation-app-store-changes/ |archive-date=15 December 2020 }}</ref> As a result of the proposal on the Digital Markets Act, Apple would be forced to change the manner in which its apps are displayed in the App Store searches, so as to give the chance to smaller developers to have their software downloaded by consumers. Moreover, Apple will have to allow its customers to uninstall preloaded first-party apps from the devices procured. Thus, both Google and Apple will be constrained and their practices more regulated. According to the DMA final proposal, these big tech companies will be compelled to share performance metrics for free with advertisers and publishers.<ref name=":17"/>

Before the official release of the DMA proposal, some companies – including Apple – tried to change their behaviour, taking into account the reactions generated by the commission's intent to regulate the digital market. As far as Apple is concerned, in October, a group of French publishers – led by {{lang|fr|italic=no|Alliance de la Presse d'Information Générale}} (APIG) – highlighted its concern with regard to the App Store's terms of service. For example, one of their requirements was related to the economic dependence on Apple – "Content publishers are in a situation of absolute economic dependence on Apple for the distribution of their content on the iPhone, since the only store available on this device is the AppStore". In addition, Apple was criticised for the 30% commission on sales that it makes through apps on the platform, thus the APIG showed its concern vis a vis the further concentration on the market.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Stolton|first=Samuel|date=19 November 2020|title=Commission has never evaluated 'deterrence effect' of antitrust fines, auditors say|url=https://www.euractiv.com/section/digital/news/commission-has-never-evaluated-deterrence-effect-of-antitrust-fines-auditors-say/|url-status=live|website=Euractiv|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201119075904/https://www.euractiv.com/section/digital/news/commission-has-never-evaluated-deterrence-effect-of-antitrust-fines-auditors-say/ |archive-date=19 November 2020 }}</ref> The reaction of Apple to these allegations was focused especially on a reduction of its commission rate to 15% for app developers with less than $1 million in annual net sales, but this did not impede the European Commission to continue advocating for the Digital Markets Act.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Pfau|first=Matthias|date=13 February 2024|title=Apple's malicious compliance: app sideloading will remain impossible on your iPhone|url=https://tuta.com/blog/apple-eu-dma-malicious-compliance|access-date=15 February 2024 }}</ref>

Similar to Google's case, Apple also seeks to limit the influence of the commission and to escape the definition of gatekeeper, so as not to become subject to further obligations. However, as Brussels still wants to outlaw gatekeepers' ability to ban others from accessing their marketplaces, firms like Spotify and Facebook – that believe Apple has set unfair conditions on those companies' apps within App Store, seem to support the commission's proposal.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Kayali|first=Laura|date=29 October 2020|title=Google goes on the offensive against EU platform rules|url=https://www.politico.eu/article/google-battles-against-eu-platform-rules/|url-status=live|access-date=12 April 2021|website=Politico|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201101121537/https://www.politico.eu/article/google-battles-against-eu-platform-rules/ |archive-date=1 November 2020 }}</ref>

The strategy of Apple to limit the influence of the DMA is not as clear or well-structured as in Google's case. However, there can be observed some practices engaged in by the company to ensure that its objectives are taken into account by the European officials. According to a research conducted by the Corporate Europe Observatory,<ref name=":18">{{Cite web|date=11 December 2020|title=Big Tech brings out the big guns in fight for future of EU tech regulation|url=https://corporateeurope.org/en/2020/12/big-tech-brings-out-big-guns-fight-future-eu-tech-regulation|url-status=live|access-date=12 April 2021|website=Corporate Europe Observatory|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201213233635/https://corporateeurope.org/en/2020/12/big-tech-brings-out-big-guns-fight-future-eu-tech-regulation |archive-date=13 December 2020 }}</ref> it seems that Apple, Google, and Facebook used to work with several associations that declared themselves independent, without disclosing their linkages. For example, the Center for European Reform has featured on its website a list of its corporate donors – one of them being Apple – but Apple does not specify this information on the Transparency Register entry.<ref name=":18"/> Under these circumstances, it can be observed the network created around interests' groups, companies, NGOs and think tanks, as all of them seek to shape the legislative process in Brussels in their favour.

When it comes to lobby spending, despite the limited and incomplete information, it can be observed that Apple is in the top 30 individual corporate lobby spenders in Brussels, at numbers 16 (with over €2 million). In comparison with Google, that has allocated a budget of €8 million, Apple still invests a considerable sum of money on access to European officials, so as to present its demands.<ref name=":18"/>

On June 24, 2024, Apple became the first company to be charged under the DMA, with regulators alleging that the company's Apple Store policies are illegal.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nytimes.com/2024/06/24/technology/apple-european-union-competition-law.html |first1=Adam |last1=Satariano |first2=Tripp |last2=Mickle |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=June 24, 2024 |title=Apple Is First Company Charged Under New E.U. Competition Law |access-date=June 25, 2024}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://cnbc.com/2024/06/24/apple-app-store-rules-are-in-breach-eu-tech-rules-regulators-say.html |first=Arjun |last=Kharpal |website=[[CNBC]] |date=June 24, 2024 |title=European Union regulators accuse Apple of breaching the bloc's tech rules |access-date=June 25, 2024}}</ref>

===ByteDance===
[[ByteDance]] is the one non-American company on the list of Gatekeepers. Its major service offering is the video hosting social network [[TikTok]].

ByteDance responded by launching a Data Portability API for EEA users, later to provide "increased access" to the API, improving the Download Your Data tool's speed and adding the ability to partially export TikTok data by allowing selections of categories to export. A webform for future DMA compliance was created.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://newsroom.tiktok.com/en-eu/tiktoks-compliance-with-the-dma | title=TikTok's compliance with the Digital Markets Act | date=16 August 2019 }}</ref>

===Meta===
Considering that the Digital Markets Act aims to limit the influence of large companies by allowing alternative players to emerge, Meta has also been targeted by the legislative proposal. As in the other companies' cases, once the DMA is adopted, unfair practices will be highly discouraged and even prohibited, so as to stop the harm they bring to competition.

However, apart from Google, Apple, and Amazon, Meta seems to support the EU rules that have been published last year.{{clarify timeframe|reason=Meaning of "last year" depends on when you're reading!|date=April 2022}} In its official declarations, Meta claimed that it hopes that the European Union will set boundaries for Apple. Nevertheless, in this context there were not observed solely tensions between the Commission and the Big Tech companies, but even between GAFAM, taking into account their statements and the objectives they advocate for.

The controversies between Meta and Apple started with the privacy feature used by Apple, that allows consumers to block advertisers from tracking them across different applications. Thus, Meta, a company that earns revenue from advertising, began to retaliate and showed its discontent. It has also added that "Apple controls an entire ecosystem from device to app store and apps, and uses this power to harm developers and consumers, as well as large platforms like Facebook".<ref name=":14">{{Cite web|date=15 December 2020|title=Facebook takes swipe at Apple while supporting draft EU rules|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/eu-tech-facebook/facebook-takes-swipe-at-apple-while-supporting-draft-eu-rules-idUSKBN28P2NS|url-status=live|website=Reuters|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201215210030/https://www.reuters.com/article/eu-tech-facebook/facebook-takes-swipe-at-apple-while-supporting-draft-eu-rules-idUSKBN28P2NS |archive-date=15 December 2020 }}</ref> The reaction of Apple was quite harsh and accused Meta of "invasive tracking".<ref name=":14"/> Therefore, the discussions around the Digital Markets Act started to create more tensions between Big Tech firms and to deviate from the scope of the proposal, as the companies focused on criticising their "competitors" of illegal practices.<ref>{{Cite web|date=16 December 2020|title=Online giants could face 10% fines under new EU law|url=https://euobserver.com/science/150396|url-status=live|access-date=2 April 2021|website=EU Observer|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201216060516/https://euobserver.com/science/150396 |archive-date=16 December 2020 }}</ref>

===Microsoft===
Microsoft was identified as gatekeeper. The consultant Cristina Caffarra and professor [[Fiona Scott Morton]] presented the view that the only obligation that might affect Microsoft under the DMA was to enable end-users to delete any software applications pre-installed.<ref name=":02"/> It is unclear whether Scott Morton was consulting already for Microsoft at the time of making such statements, her consulting work for Microsoft became known during the [[Fiona Scott Morton#Appointment to EU position and withdrawal|Fiona Scott Morton affair]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Lesnes|first=Corine|date=17 July 2023 |title=Fiona Scott Morton 'is a Trojan horse for Big Tech' at the European Commission |url=https://www.lemonde.fr/en/economy/article/2023/07/17/fiona-scott-morton-is-a-trojan-horse-for-big-tech-at-the-european-commission_6056267_19.html |work=Le Monde|location= |access-date=7 October 2023}}</ref>

Microsoft complied by allowing worldwide users to uninstall Camera, Photos, and Cortana, and EEA users to uninstall Bing Web Search and Microsoft Edge. APIs for custom search engines and widget feeds were created for EEA exclusive users. EEA users will also be prompted about syncing a PC's data to Microsoft.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://blogs.windows.com/windows-insider/2023/11/16/previewing-changes-in-windows-to-comply-with-the-digital-markets-act-in-the-european-economic-area/ | title=Previewing changes in Windows to comply with the Digital Markets Act in the European Economic Area | date=16 November 2023 }}</ref> A registry hack was shortly created to get these changes without living in an EEA country or having to move to an EEA country.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.neowin.net/guides/how-to-remove-microsoft-edge-from-windows-11-in-the-latest-eea-compliant-update/ | title=How to remove Microsoft Edge from Windows 11 in the latest EEA-compliant update }}</ref> EEA users are no longer advertised about Microsoft Edge.

==Non-Gatekeeper firms==

===Airbnb and Booking.com===
Due to their important positions on the short-term accommodation market, [[Airbnb]] and [[Booking.com]] became potential targets for the legislation. Indeed, above 50% of the homes designated for 'short-terms stay' are listed on AirBnB, and approximatively 30% on Booking.com.<ref name=":8">{{Cite news|last1=Espinoza|first1=Javier|last2=Hancock|first2=Alice|date=2020-11-08|title=EU debates hitting Airbnb with tougher regulation|work=Financial Times|url=https://www.ft.com/content/71c9635a-a7d7-4b10-9d60-90c4b585c3d1|access-date=2022-04-12|archive-date=14 May 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210514122125/https://www.ft.com/content/71c9635a-a7d7-4b10-9d60-90c4b585c3d1|url-status=live}}</ref> Therefore, their possible labelling as gatekeepers has been long debated, leading the companies to defend themselves and explain why they should not be considered included in this category.<ref>{{Cite web|date=2020-12-14|title=Big guns and Zoom cliques: Inside Silicon Valley's digital lobbying playbook|url=https://www.politico.eu/article/europe-digital-lobbying-platforms/|access-date=2022-04-12|website=POLITICO|language=en-US|archive-date=27 April 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210427162732/https://www.politico.eu/article/europe-digital-lobbying-platforms/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|last=Stolton|first=Samuel|date=2020-12-16|title=Commission vies to 'put order into chaos' with new digital crackdown|url=https://www.euractiv.com/section/digital/news/commission-vies-to-put-order-into-chaos-with-new-digital-crackdown/|access-date=2022-04-12|website=www.euractiv.com|language=en-GB|archive-date=10 March 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210310173933/https://www.euractiv.com/section/digital/news/commission-vies-to-put-order-into-chaos-with-new-digital-crackdown/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=":9">{{Cite web|date=2020-12-14|title=Digital Market Act…: Booking refuse d'être régulé comme un géant de la tech|url=https://www.lefigaro.fr/secteur/high-tech/digital-market-act-booking-refuse-d-etre-regule-comme-un-geant-de-la-tech-20201214|access-date=2022-04-12|website=LEFIGARO|language=fr|archive-date=2 June 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210602113023/https://www.lefigaro.fr/secteur/high-tech/digital-market-act-booking-refuse-d-etre-regule-comme-un-geant-de-la-tech-20201214|url-status=live}}</ref> Moreover, Booking.com insisted on the fact that it is one of the only European companies that is a global success and that as they are not the most dominant actor in this sector, they should not be disincentivized while competing with bigger companies.<ref name=":9"/>

===Spotify===
With approximately one third of the market share in the music subscription market in 2020, [[Spotify]] is by far the dominant actor in this sector, with [[Apple Music]] coming in second position, with around 15% of market share.<ref name=":10">{{Cite web |last=Trainer |first=David |title=It Sounds Like Spotify Is In Trouble |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/greatspeculations/2020/10/13/it-sounds-like-spotify-is-in-trouble/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210326210139/https://www.forbes.com/sites/greatspeculations/2020/10/13/it-sounds-like-spotify-is-in-trouble/ |archive-date=26 March 2021 |access-date=2021-03-30 |website=Forbes |language=en}}</ref> However, Spotify does not seem to meet the criteria set by the European Commission, according to the analysis of ''Vox EU''.<ref name=":02"/> Dirk Auer, an economist of the American think tank ICLE, qualified this piece of legislation as a way to protect the European firms, and that the criteria are on purpose excluding major European tech firms, notably Spotify.<ref>{{Cite web|last=ULiège|first=Dirk Auer |date=2020-12-17|title=The Flaws in Europe's Digital Markets Regulation|url=https://www.euractiv.com/section/all/opinion/the-flaws-in-europes-digital-markets-regulation/|access-date=2022-04-12|website=Euractiv |language=en-GB|archive-date=28 February 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210228131331/https://www.euractiv.com/section/all/opinion/the-flaws-in-europes-digital-markets-regulation/|url-status=live}}</ref> Even if it is true that SAP would probably be the only European firm targeted by the legal act,<ref name=":02"/> there are also American big platforms like Twitter or Uber not targeted by the legislation, despite their important market position.<ref name=":02"/>

===Samsung===
Although [[Samsung]] had appeared earlier on a list of possible gatekeepers,<ref>{{Cite web |title=Remarks by Commissioner Breton: Here are the first 7 potential "Gatekeepers" under the EU Digital Markets Act|url=https://ec.europa.eu/commission/presscorner/detail/en/STATEMENT_23_3674 |access-date=2023-09-15 |website=European Commission - European Commission |language=en}}</ref> it was not on the final list.

=== X (Twitter) ===
In October 2024, the European Commission decided that [[X (formerly known as Twitter)]] is not considered a gatekeeper in online social networking, as it is "not an important gateway for business users to reach end users."<ref>{{Cite web |title=Commission concludes that online social networking service of X should not be designated under the Digital Markets Act |url=https://digital-markets-act.ec.europa.eu/commission-concludes-online-social-networking-service-x-should-not-be-designated-under-digital-2024-10-16_en |access-date=2024-10-16 |website=digital-markets-act.ec.europa.eu |language=en}}</ref>

==Reaction within the European Union==
===France===
The French Government expressed its ambition for imposing stricter enforcement on competition rules, so as to prevent giant tech firms favouring their own services, ousting rivals or maintaining their dominant positions.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Grandes plateformes du numérique: vers le Digital Services Act et Digital Markets Act|url=https://www.economie.gouv.fr/digital-services-act-et-digital-markets-act|access-date=2021-04-12|website=www.economie.gouv.fr|language=fr|archive-date=17 April 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210417081121/https://www.economie.gouv.fr/digital-services-act-et-digital-markets-act|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=":132">{{Cite web|publisher=Ministerie van Economische Zaken en Klimaat|date=2020-10-15|title=Considerations of France, Belgium and the Netherlands regarding intervention on platforms with a gatekeeper position – Report|location=Netherlands|url=https://www.government.nl/documents/publications/2020/10/15/considerations-of-france-and-the-netherlands-regarding-intervention-on-platforms-with-a-gatekeeper-position|access-date=2021-04-12|language=en-GB|archive-date=12 April 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210412172719/https://www.government.nl/documents/publications/2020/10/15/considerations-of-france-and-the-netherlands-regarding-intervention-on-platforms-with-a-gatekeeper-position|url-status=live}}</ref>

Nevertheless, France would like to rely on the possibility of adapting the rules, through the Digital Markets Act, in order to respond to the constant changes of the digital market.<ref name="Stolton">{{Cite web|last=Stolton|first=Samuel|date=2020-12-18|title=Digital Brief, powered by Google: DSA and DMA – member states respond|url=https://www.euractiv.com/section/digital/news/digital-brief-powered-by-google-dsa-and-dma-member-states-respond/|access-date=2021-04-12|website=Euractiv|archive-date=13 April 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210413133832/https://www.euractiv.com/section/digital/news/digital-brief-powered-by-google-dsa-and-dma-member-states-respond/|url-status=live}}</ref>  

The French government is known to be publicly in favour of more regulation of the GAFAM<ref>{{Cite web|last=the Guardian|date=2020-01-12|title=France's digital minister says tax on big tech is just the start|url=http://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/12/frances-digital-minister-tax-on-tech-giants-just-the-start-cedric-o-gafa|url-status=live|access-date=2021-04-13|website=the Guardian|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200112182849/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/12/frances-digital-minister-tax-on-tech-giants-just-the-start-cedric-o-gafa |archive-date=12 January 2020 }}</ref> and unilaterally set up its "{{ill|GAFA tax|fr|taxe GAFA}}" in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Taxation: the outlines of the GAFA tax revealed|url=https://www.gouvernement.fr/en/taxation-the-outlines-of-the-gafa-tax-revealed|access-date=2022-04-12|website=Gouvernement.fr|language=en|archive-date=13 April 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210413041842/https://www.gouvernement.fr/en/taxation-the-outlines-of-the-gafa-tax-revealed|url-status=live}}</ref> This tax was the source of tensions with the Trump administration.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Le Monde|date=2019-12-03|title=Taxe GAFA: Washington menace de surtaxer des produits français jusqu'à 100 %|language=fr|work=Le Monde|url=https://www.lemonde.fr/economie/article/2019/12/03/taxe-gafa-washington-menace-de-surtaxer-des-produits-francais-jusqu-a-100_6021408_3234.html|access-date=2021-04-13|archive-date=13 April 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210413104503/https://www.lemonde.fr/economie/article/2019/12/03/taxe-gafa-washington-menace-de-surtaxer-des-produits-francais-jusqu-a-100_6021408_3234.html|url-status=live}}</ref>

===Germany===
The German federal government welcomed the proposal on the Digital Markets Act. They consider that the current European legal framework is not sufficiently strong and that the enforcement measures must also be strengthened with respect to digital platforms.<ref name=":142">{{Cite web|last=Stolton|first=Samuel|date=2020-10-30|title=Germany weighs in on EU's bid to regulate digital giants|url=https://www.euractiv.com/section/digital/news/germany-weighs-in-on-eus-bid-to-regulate-digital-giants/|access-date=2021-04-12|website=Euractiv|archive-date=8 May 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210508111109/https://www.euractiv.com/section/digital/news/germany-weighs-in-on-eus-bid-to-regulate-digital-giants/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="Stolton"/> However, the main concern of Germany still remains the preservation of small and medium-sized companies, as it intends to keep them out of the scope of the new rules.<ref name=":142"/>

The head of the German Federal Cartel Office, Andreas Mundt, has on several occasions criticised the European Commission's centralised approach to regulating gatekeepers.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2021-12-20 |title=German competition chief sees vanguard digital role at risk |url=https://www.politico.eu/article/germany-competition-chief-sees-vanguard-digital-role-risk/ |access-date=2022-04-12 |website=POLITICO |language=en-US |archive-date=12 April 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220412103831/https://www.politico.eu/article/germany-competition-chief-sees-vanguard-digital-role-risk/ |url-status=live }}</ref> He has called the European Commission's veto right over national competition authorities' powers to impose decisions against Big Tech "unacceptable", and has asked for more powers to be given to national competition authorities.<ref>{{Cite web |title=MLex {{!}} Insight and Comment on Regulatory Risk for Law Firms, Corporations and Hedge Funds |url=https://content.mlex.com/#/content/1366214?referrer=portfolio_openrelatedcontent |access-date=2022-04-12 |website=content.mlex.com |archive-date=12 April 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220412130421/https://content.mlex.com/#/content/1366214?referrer=portfolio_openrelatedcontent |url-status=live }}</ref> This position was echoed by other Member States.<ref>[https://www.bmwi.de/Redaktion/DE/Downloads/M-O/non-paper-friends-of-an-effective-digital-markets-act.pdf?__blob=publicationFile&v=6 Non paper friends of an effective digital markets act] bmwi.de
{{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211102083357/https://www.bmwi.de/Redaktion/DE/Downloads/M-O/non-paper-friends-of-an-effective-digital-markets-act.pdf?__blob=publicationFile&v=6 |date=2 November 2021 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://competition-policy.ec.europa.eu/antitrust-and-cartels/european-competition-network_en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220412103904/https://ec.europa.eu/competition/ecn/DMA_joint_EU_NCAs_paper_21.06.2021.pdf|title=European Competition Network|archive-date=12 April 2022|website=competition-policy.ec.europa.eu}}</ref>

===Netherlands===
In October 2020, the Dutch Government jointly with France and Belgium, expressed their willingness for a stricter enforcement of the competition rules, in order to avoid abuse of dominance and anti-competitive practices.<ref name=":132"/>

On 17 February 2021, the Dutch Government published its official position on the Digital Markets Act<ref>{{Cite web|last=Dutch Government|date=17 February 2021|title=Dutch position on the proposal for the Digital Markets Act|url=https://www.permanentrepresentations.nl/documents/publications/2021/02/17/dutch-position-on-the-proposal-for-the-digital-markets-act|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210301131828/https://www.permanentrepresentations.nl/documents/publications/2021/02/17/dutch-position-on-the-proposal-for-the-digital-markets-act |archive-date=1 March 2021 }}</ref> and welcomed the initiative, taking into account that the objectives it comprises are aligned with their national position.

===Ireland===
The Irish government published its position on 8 September 2020, during the public consultations held for the Digital Services Act Package.<ref name=":15">{{Cite web|title=National submission to the EU consultation on the Digital Services Act package|date=17 September 2020 |url=https://digitalmarket.sg/learn/national-submission-to-the-eu-consultation-on-the-digital-services-act-package/|access-date=2021-04-12|publisher=Government of Ireland|language=en|archive-date=12 April 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210412172726/https://digitalmarket.sg/learn/national-submission-to-the-eu-consultation-on-the-digital-services-act-package/|url-status=live}}</ref> According to their statements, Irish authorities are not willing to assess the definition of "gatekeepers", as they explained that the occupation of a dominant position is not illegal. Moreover, they have also stressed that this particular aspect does not imply a diminution of consumer welfare and does not prevent innovation or new entrances in the digital market.<ref name=":15"/>

Many of the companies that are likely to be targeted by the DMA have their headquarters in Ireland.<ref name=":19">{{Cite news|last=Espinoza|first=Javier|date=2021-03-17|title=Simmering tensions about alleged lack of enforcement by Dublin burst into public|url=https://www.ft.com/content/37705bcf-c5b6-4ef0-adb8-35a8680dbaec|url-status=live|access-date=2021-04-13|newspaper=Financial Times|archive-date=13 April 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210413053126/https://www.ft.com/content/37705bcf-c5b6-4ef0-adb8-35a8680dbaec}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=2021-11-25 |title=Europe reins in Big Tech: What you need to know |url=https://www.politico.eu/article/europe-digital-markets-act-dma-digital-services-act-dsa-regulation-platforms-google-amazon-facebook-apple-microsoft/ |access-date=2022-07-21 |website=POLITICO |language=en-US |archive-date=21 July 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220721192436/https://www.politico.eu/article/europe-digital-markets-act-dma-digital-services-act-dsa-regulation-platforms-google-amazon-facebook-apple-microsoft/ |url-status=live }}</ref> The approach of the Irish Government towards Big Tech companies has often been the source of debates within the European Union.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Murray|first=Shona|date=2021-03-02|title=EU member states push forward with new tax transparency rules|url=https://www.euronews.com/2021/03/02/eu-member-states-push-forward-with-new-tax-transparency-rules|access-date=2021-04-13|website=Euronews|language=en|archive-date=13 April 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210413095554/https://www.euronews.com/2021/03/02/eu-member-states-push-forward-with-new-tax-transparency-rules|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=":19"/> In 2016, the European Commission [[EU illegal state aid case against Apple in Ireland|accused Ireland of granting Apple "illegal tax benefits"]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Houlder|first=Vanessa|date=2016-08-30|title=Apple's EU tax dispute explained|work=Financial Times|url=https://www.ft.com/content/3e0172a0-6e1b-11e6-9ac1-1055824ca907|access-date=2021-04-13|archive-date=13 April 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210413081239/https://www.ft.com/content/3e0172a0-6e1b-11e6-9ac1-1055824ca907|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[General Court (European Union)|General Court]] ruled in favour of Apple, but the Commission expressed its intention to appeal the ruling to the [[European Court of Justice]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Espinoza|first=Javier|date=2020-09-25|title=Brussels to appeal against court decision quashing Apple tax order|work=Financial Times|url=https://www.ft.com/content/058d380a-a0fa-40b7-95f9-1867378daf99|access-date=2021-04-13|archive-date=13 April 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210413095608/https://www.ft.com/content/058d380a-a0fa-40b7-95f9-1867378daf99|url-status=live}}</ref>

==Rest of the world's position==
As with other pieces of complex legislation (the '[[Brussels effect]]'), other countries have taken steps to copy the DMA.<ref name="cepa">[https://cepa.org/article/europes-dma-goes-global/ Europe's DMA Goes Global], March 4, 2024</ref>

===Brazil===
Draft legislation has been launched to implement a regulatory framework inspired by the European Union's Digital Markets Act.<ref>{{cite journal | url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0267364924000049 | doi=10.1016/j.clsr.2024.105937 | title=Lost in translation? Critically assessing the promises and perils of Brazil's Digital Markets Act proposal in the light of international experiments | date=2024 | last1=Fernandes | first1=Victor Oliveira | journal=Computer Law & Security Review | volume=52 | url-access=subscription }}</ref><ref name="cepa"/>

===India===
The Indian government is considering a  DMA-styled regulatory approach to apply to "systemically important digital intermediaries. However, as of April 2024 no concrete proposals were done.<ref name="cepa"/>

===Japan===
Japan is reworking its competition laws and regulations in order to more close resemble the regulatory structure of the European Union.<ref>[https://www.aei.org/technology-and-innovation/japans-precarious-digital-markets-crossroads/ Japan's Precarious Digital Markets Crossroads], January 2023</ref>

===South Korea===
The "Promotion of Platform competition" is modeled on the DMA,<ref name="cepa"/> but is currently delayed.

===United Kingdom===
The [[Digital Markets, Competition and Consumers Act 2024]], granting powers to the [[Competition and Markets Authority]] to regulate technology companies with strategic market power, has been passed by [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Parliament]] and was granted [[royal assent]] to become law on 24 May 2024.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Digital Markets, Competition and Consumers Act receives Royal Assent |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/digital-markets-competition-and-consumers-act-receives-royal-assent |access-date=2024-05-24 |website=GOV.UK |language=en}}</ref>

===United States===
{{Outdated|part=section|date=April 2025|reason=Trump administration}}
This legislation comes in a context where the EU and the US, under the Biden administration, want to rebuild better relations after the tensions that emerged during the [[First presidency of Donald Trump|Trump presidency]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Landler|first=Mark|date=2020-11-07|title=Biden Victory Brings Sighs of Relief Overseas|language=en-US|work=The New York Times|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/11/07/world/americas/biden-international-reaction.html|access-date=2022-04-12|issn=0362-4331|archive-date=16 December 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211216084017/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/11/07/world/americas/biden-international-reaction.html|url-status=live}}</ref> The European Commission has stressed the need for cooperation between the EU and the US in dealing with the dominant positions of online platforms and big tech which they consider harmful.<ref name=":11">{{Cite web |title=Proposal for a regulation of the European Parliament and of the Council on contestable and fair markets in the digital sector (Digital Markets Act) |url=https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/?uri=CELEX%3A52020PC0842 |access-date=2022-10-13 |website=[[EUR-Lex]] |language=en |publication-date=2020-12-15 |archive-date=11 November 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221111083748/https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/?uri=CELEX%3A52020PC0842 |url-status=live }}</ref>
In January 2021, the President of the European Commission, [[Ursula von der Leyen]], stated that the then-current president of the United States, Joe Biden, and the European Union share the same position regarding the regulation of tech companies.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Amaro|first=Silvia|date=2021-01-20|title=Europe and Biden 'on the same page' over Big Tech regulation, EU chief says|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2021/01/20/eu-chief-says-biden-on-the-same-page-over-big-tech-regulation.html|access-date=2021-04-13|website=CNBC|language=en|archive-date=13 April 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210413053858/https://www.cnbc.com/2021/01/20/eu-chief-says-biden-on-the-same-page-over-big-tech-regulation.html|url-status=live}}</ref> In a speech at the [[Munich Security Conference]] in February 2021 she invited the United States to join the European Union in its initiatives in order to create rules in the digital Economy that can be "valid worldwide".<ref>{{Cite web |title=Speech by President von der Leyen at the Special Edition 2021 of the Munich Security Conference |url=https://ec.europa.eu/commission/presscorner/detail/en/SPEECH_21_706 |access-date=2022-04-12 |website=European Commission - European Commission |language=en |archive-date=13 April 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210413030701/https://ec.europa.eu/commission/presscorner/detail/en/SPEECH_21_706 |url-status=live }}</ref>

Even if the official position of the Biden administration on the Digital Markets Act is not yet publicly known, the same debates about the dominant position of some digital tech platforms are rising in the United States.<ref>{{Cite news|last1=Stacey|first1=Kiran|last2=Waters|first2=Richard|date=2020-11-08|title=What can Silicon Valley expect from Joe Biden?|work=Financial Times|url=https://www.ft.com/content/44f738e8-eb6f-4394-b833-6b3207ce31bf|access-date=2022-04-12|archive-date=29 April 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210429064704/https://www.ft.com/content/44f738e8-eb6f-4394-b833-6b3207ce31bf|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last1=Kang|first1=Cecilia|last2=McCabe|first2=David|date=2020-10-06|title=House Lawmakers Condemn Big Tech's 'Monopoly Power' and Urge Their Breakups|language=en-US|work=The New York Times|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/10/06/technology/congress-big-tech-monopoly-power.html|access-date=2022-04-12|issn=0362-4331|archive-date=31 March 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210331085128/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/10/06/technology/congress-big-tech-monopoly-power.html|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Ovide|first=Shira|date=2020-07-30|title=Big Tech's Backlash Is Just Starting|language=en-US|work=The New York Times|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/07/30/technology/big-tech-backlash.html|access-date=2022-04-12|issn=0362-4331|archive-date=16 March 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210316054320/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/07/30/technology/big-tech-backlash.html|url-status=live}}</ref> An [[Federal Trade Commission v. Facebook|antitrust lawsuit]] was opened in December 2020 against Facebook by the US [[Federal Trade Commission]] and 46 American states for abusing its dominant position and exercising anti-competitive conduct for several years.<ref>{{Cite web|date=2020-12-09|title=FTC Sues Facebook for Illegal Monopolization|url=http://www.ftc.gov/news-events/news/press-releases/2020/12/ftc-sues-facebook-illegal-monopolization|access-date=2022-04-12|website=Federal Trade Commission|language=en|archive-date=11 April 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220411165358/https://www.ftc.gov/news-events/news/press-releases/2020/12/ftc-sues-facebook-illegal-monopolization|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Murphy|first=Hannah|date=2020-12-09|title=US sues Facebook for 'years-long' abuse of monopoly power|work=Financial Times|url=https://www.ft.com/content/5c03ac0f-7122-4c31-97a5-ecab3928a038|access-date=2022-04-12|archive-date=17 February 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210217201355/https://www.ft.com/content/5c03ac0f-7122-4c31-97a5-ecab3928a038|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|date=2020-12-09|title=U.S. states to sue Facebook for antitrust violations on Wednesday, sources say|language=en|work=Reuters|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/tech-antitrust-facebook-states-idUSKBN28J1XM|access-date=2022-04-12|archive-date=18 February 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210218001636/https://www.reuters.com/article/tech-antitrust-facebook-states-idUSKBN28J1XM|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=U.S., states sue Facebook as an illegal monopoly, setting stage for potential breakup|language=en-US|newspaper=Washington Post|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2020/12/09/facebook-antitrust-lawsuit/|access-date=2022-04-12|issn=0190-8286|archive-date=7 February 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210207115421/https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2020/12/09/facebook-antitrust-lawsuit/|url-status=live}}</ref>

In a document published in March 2021, the [[Congressional Research Service]], an American government [[think tank]] that informs the members of the [[US Congress]], outlined the fact that the new digital regulations led by the European Union, including the Digital Markets Act, could be sources of potential future cooperation between the EU and the United States, while stressing the potential impact on the US economy.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Fefer|first=Rachel|date=2021-03-25|title=EU Digital Policy and International Trade|url=https://crsreports.congress.gov/product/details?prodcode=R46732|url-status=live|access-date=2021-04-13|publisher=United States Congress|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210413043749/https://crsreports.congress.gov/product/details?prodcode=R46732 |archive-date=13 April 2021 }}</ref>

== Violations and fines ==
In April 2025,  Apple and Meta became the first companies to be penalized for violating the Digital Markets Act. Apple was fined 500 million euros ($570 million) and Meta was fined 200 million euros ($230 million) respectively.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Satariano |first=Adam |date=2025-04-23 |title=EU Fines Apple and Meta Total of $800 Million in First Use of Digital Competition Law |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2025/04/23/technology/apple-meta-eu-fines-competition-law.html |access-date=2025-04-23 |work=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref>

